Ringgit Strengthens on Easing Greece Debt Concern, Rate Outlook

-- B y   E l f f i e   C h e w
-- 
2011-06-24T08:46:45Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-24/ringgit-strengthens-on-easing-greece-debt-concern-rate-outlook.html
Malaysia’s ringgit rose on
speculation accelerating inflation may prompt policy makers to
favor appreciation or raise benchmark interest rates.  The currency rebounded from its biggest loss in two weeks
before a government report due at 5 p.m. today that may show
consumer prices quickened to 3.3 percent in May from a year
earlier, the most since March 2009, according to a Bloomberg
News survey. European Union leaders yesterday pledged to
stabilize the euro-area economy, vowing to stave off a Greek
default as long as Prime Minister  George Papandreou  pushes
through a package of budget cuts next week.  “The relief rally in the euro following  Greece ’s ability
to get support from the EU is helping most Asian currencies,”
said Patrick Hu, a strategist at CIMB Investment Bank Bhd. in
 Kuala Lumpur . “The ringgit is also pricing-in expectations of a
higher-than-expected inflation rate for May.”  The ringgit increased 0.1 percent to 3.0418 per dollar as
of 4:35 p.m. in Kuala Lumpur, according to data compiled by
Bloomberg. The currency is 0.3 percent weaker than a week ago.  Bank Negara Malaysia raised its overnight policy rate to 3
percent from 2.75 percent on May 5. Borrowing costs may rise to
3.25 percent by the end of this year, according to the median
estimate of economists in a Bloomberg News survey. The bank will
meet next on July 7 to review rates.  Malaysian  government bonds  gained. The yield on the 4.262
percent notes due September 2016 fell one basis point or 0.01
percentage point to 3.50 percent this week, according to Bursa
Malaysia.  The treasury will sell two billion ringgit ($657 million)
of 20-year notes maturing in June 2031 at an auction on June 29,
 Bank Negara Malaysia  announced on its website yesterday. It last
sold similar-maturity debt in April 2010.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Sandy Hendry at 
 shendry@bloomberg.net  